{"id":"0708.2202","submitter":"Alfons Van Daele","authors":"A. Van Daele","title":"Locally compact quantum groups. Radford's $S^4$ formula","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.QA math.OA","license":null,"abstract":"  Let $A$ be a finite-dimensional Hopf algebra. The left and the right\nintegrals on $A$ are related by means of a distinguished group-like element\n$\\delta$ of $A$. Similarly, there is this element $\\hat\\delta$ in the dual Hopf\nalgebra $\\hat A$. Radford showed that\n$$S^4(a)=\\delta^{-1}(\\hat\\delta\\triangleright a \\triangleleft\n\\hat\\delta^{-1})\\delta$$ for all $a$ in $A$ where $S$ is the antipode of $A$\nand where $\\triangleright$ and $\\triangleleft$ are used to denote the standard\nleft and right actions of $\\hat A$ on $A$. The formula still holds for\nmultiplier Hopf algebras with integrals (algebraic quantum groups).\n  In the theory of locally compact quantum groups, an analytical form of\nRadford's formula can be proven (in terms of bounded operators on a Hilbert\nspace).\n  In this talk, we do not have the intention to discuss Radford's formula as\nsuch, but rather to use it, together with related formulas, for illustrating\nvarious aspects of the road that takes us from the theory of Hopf algebras\n(including compact quantum groups) to multiplier Hopf algebras (including\ndiscrete quantum groups) and further to the more general theory of locally\ncompact quantum groups.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 16 Aug 2007 13:52:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-08-17"}
